Reading Fold-to-Fold Variability



collect_metrics(cv_results, summarize = FALSE) |&gt;
  filter(.metric == "roc_auc") |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(x = id, y = .estimate)) + geom_col()

Wide spread across folds → performance is sensitive to which prospects end up in the assessment set. Worth investigating before trusting the model.

5.1 The Resubstitution Problem
What happens if we evaluate the model on the same data it was trained on?


Code
train_preds &lt;- augment(mail_fit, new_data = mail_train)

bind_rows(
  train_preds |&gt;
    class_metrics(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(data = "training (resubstitution)"),
  test_preds |&gt;
    class_metrics(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(data = "test (held out)")
) |&gt;
  select(data, .metric, .estimate) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = data, values_from = .estimate)













Important



Resubstitution is optimistic. The model has already “seen” the training data and partially memorized its noise, so performance measured there is inflated relative to how the model will do on genuinely new prospects. This gap is usually small for simple models like regularized logistic regression, but it can be large for flexible models (deep trees, boosted ensembles) — which is exactly why we need a principled way to estimate out-of-sample performance without permanently sacrificing data to a single test set.

2.3 Exercise 9.3 — Regression Metric Sensitivity to Outliers


Code
# Original metrics
original_metrics &lt;- reg_preds |&gt;
  metric_set(rmse, mae)(truth = order_value_next, estimate = .pred)

# Add one "whale" customer
whale_row &lt;- tibble(
  order_value_next = 5000,
  .pred = 200
)

reg_preds_whale &lt;- bind_rows(
  reg_preds |&gt; select(order_value_next, .pred),
  whale_row
)

# Metrics with whale
whale_metrics &lt;- reg_preds_whale |&gt;
  metric_set(rmse, mae)(truth = order_value_next, estimate = .pred)

# Compare
bind_rows(
  original_metrics |&gt; mutate(data = "without whale"),
  whale_metrics |&gt; mutate(data = "with whale")
) |&gt;
  select(data, .metric, .estimate) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = data, values_from = .estimate) |&gt;
  mutate(
    pct_change = round(
      (`with whale` - `without whale`) / `without whale` * 100,
      1
    )
  )













NoteRMSE vs. MAE: Which is More Sensitive to Outliers?



RMSE moves more in percentage terms because it squares the error before averaging — a $4,800 prediction error ($5,000 − $200) becomes a $23M squared error, which dominates the average. MAE only takes the absolute value, so the same whale contributes a $4,800 error that is large but proportional.
Marketing implication: If your dataset contains occasional very large orders (“whales”), RMSE will be heavily influenced by how well the model predicts those customers. MAE gives a more representative picture of typical prediction accuracy for the average customer. In practice, it is worth reporting both and noting when they diverge significantly — a large RMSE/MAE gap signals the presence of influential outliers.

3.2 Exercise 10.2 — Bootstrap vs. Cross-Validation


Code
# Run fit_resamples with bootstrap
boot_results &lt;- fit_resamples(
  mail_wf,
  resamples = boot_resamples,
  metrics = metric_set(accuracy, roc_auc, sens, spec)
)

# Compare bootstrap vs 10-fold CV
bind_rows(
  collect_metrics(cv_results) |&gt;
    filter(.metric == "roc_auc") |&gt;
    select(mean, std_err) |&gt;
    mutate(method = "10-fold CV"),
  collect_metrics(boot_results) |&gt;
    filter(.metric == "roc_auc") |&gt;
    select(mean, std_err) |&gt;
    mutate(method = "Bootstrap (25 resamples)")
) |&gt;
  select(method, mean, std_err)













NoteBootstrap vs. Cross-Validation



The mean roc_auc from bootstrap and 10-fold CV should be close — both are estimating the same underlying population quantity. However, they typically differ in their standard errors:

Bootstrap tends to produce a smaller standard error because each bootstrap resample uses the full training data (sampled with replacement), giving each assessment more coverage of the data space
Cross-validation assessment sets are strictly held-out, so they are smaller and more variable

The trade-off: bootstrap estimates can be slightly optimistic because some training observations appear in both the analysis set and the assessment set of the same resample (about 63% of observations appear at least once in each bootstrap sample). Cross-validation avoids this — every assessment observation is completely held out from its fold’s training data.

3.4 Exercise 10.4 — Resubstitution Gap and Model Flexibility

3.4.1 Part A — Observe the Gap


Code
# Fit a random forest
#install.packages("ranger")
library(ranger)
rf_spec &lt;- rand_forest() |&gt;
  set_engine("ranger") |&gt;
  set_mode("classification")

rf_wf &lt;- mail_wf |&gt; update_model(rf_spec)
rf_fit &lt;- fit(rf_wf, data = mail_train)

rf_train_preds &lt;- augment(rf_fit, new_data = mail_train)
rf_test_preds &lt;- augment(rf_fit, new_data = mail_test)




Code
# Compare resubstitution vs. held-out for both models
bind_rows(
  rf_train_preds |&gt;
    accuracy(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(model = "Random Forest", data = "train (resubstitution)"),
  rf_test_preds |&gt;
    accuracy(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(model = "Random Forest", data = "test (held out)"),
  train_preds |&gt;
    accuracy(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(model = "Lasso LR", data = "train (resubstitution)"),
  test_preds |&gt;
    accuracy(truth = responded, estimate = .pred_class) |&gt;
    mutate(model = "Lasso LR", data = "test (held out)")
) |&gt;
  select(model, data, .estimate) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = data, values_from = .estimate) |&gt;
  mutate(
    gap = round(
      `train (resubstitution)` - `test (held out)`,
      4
    )
  )









3.4.2 Part B — Explain the Gap






NoteWhy the Random Forest Shows a Larger Gap



Q1 — Is the gap larger for random forest? Yes — almost always. The random forest’s resubstitution accuracy is typically near 1.0 (it essentially memorizes the training data), while its test accuracy is closer to the Lasso’s test accuracy. The Lasso shows a much smaller gap.
Q2 — Why does flexibility cause a larger gap? A random forest is a highly flexible model — it can grow very deep trees that carve the feature space into tiny regions, each fitted to a small group of training observations including their noise. This is called overfitting: the model learns the training data so well that it memorizes patterns that don’t generalize to new prospects.
The Lasso penalizes coefficient magnitude, forcing a simpler model that ignores noise. It deliberately accepts slightly worse training-set performance in exchange for better generalization — which is why its resubstitution gap is small.
Q3 — Why is resubstitution unreliable for model comparison? If you compared Lasso and random forest on training-set accuracy alone, the random forest would always win (it fits training data almost perfectly by design). But that advantage vanishes on new data. This is exactly why we use cross-validation or a held-out test set to compare models — it forces both models to be evaluated on data they have not seen, giving an honest comparison of which generalizes better to new prospects.

